theorem:410D:
\paragraph{Context}
The theorem concerns the order condition for a linear multistep method $[\alpha, \beta]$. The preceding text derives an alternative form of the order condition by substituting $\exp(z)$ with $(1+z)^{-1}$ and using the power series for $\log(1+z)$. Here, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the polynomials associated with the method, typically $\alpha(z) = \alpha_k z^k + \alpha_{k-1} z^{k-1} + \dots + \alpha_0$ and $\beta(z) = \beta_k z^k + \beta_{k-1} z^{k-1} + \dots + \beta_0$. The order of the method is $p$. For $|z|<1$, $\log(1+z)$ is defined by its power series: $\log(1+z) = z - \frac{1}{2}z^2 + \frac{1}{3}z^3 - \dotsb$. The derived condition is
\begin{equation}
\alpha\!\big((1+z)^{-1}\big) - \log(1+z)\,\beta\!\big((1+z)^{-1}\big) = O(z^{p+1}).
\tag{410d}
\end{equation}

