theorem:520B:
\paragraph{Context}
The theorem concerns stability analysis of general linear methods applied to the linear test equation
\begin{equation}
y'(x)=qy(x). \tag{520a}
\end{equation}
Let \(z=hq\) where \(h\) is the step size. For a method defined by matrices \((A,U,B,V)\), the stability matrix is
\[
M(z)=V+zB(I-zA)^{-1}U.
\]
Applying one step yields the relation
\begin{equation}
y^{[n]}=M(z)y^{[n-1]}, \tag{520b}
\end{equation}
where \(y^{[n-1]}\) and \(y^{[n]}\) are the incoming and output vectors of approximations.

definition:520C:
\paragraph{Context}
