The theorem concerns the stability region of a general linear method defined by $(A, U, B, V)$, where $M(z)$ is the stability matrix and $\Phi(w, z)$ is the stability polynomial (or rational function). The stability region consists of complex $z$ such that the powers of $M(z)$ are bounded.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $M(z)$: stability matrix for the general linear method $(A, U, B, V)$
    \item $\Phi(w, z)$: stability function, defined as $\det(wI - M(z))$ (or its numerator if rational)
\end{itemize}

definition:520E:
\paragraph{Context}
The discussion concerns stability properties of general linear methods for ODEs, focusing on the stability matrix \(M(z)\) and the stability function \(\Phi(w,z)\). The stability region is defined in terms of boundedness of powers of \(M(z)\).

\begin{itemize}
    \item \(M(z)\): stability matrix, a matrix function of \(z\)
    \item \(\Phi(w, z)\): stability function, given by \(\Phi(w, z) = \det(wI - M(z))\)
    \item stability region: subset of the complex plane such that if \(z\) is in this subset, then \(\sup_{n=1}^{\infty} \|M(z)^n\| < \infty\)
    \item instability region: complement of the stability region
    \item power-bounded: a matrix \(M\) is power-bounded if \(\sup_{n \geq 1} \|M^n\| < \infty\)
\end{itemize}

